Title: From Heaven Lake: Travels Through Sinkiang and Tibet
Author: Vikram Seth
My Review: Really enjoyed it. I like Seth's narrative voice during the travel--perceptive and human, but not too self-congratulatory or pretentious or any of the other things that sometimes get on my nerves in travel writing. I don't have any particular interest in Tibet, but it was interesting to see how it looked, to him, in the early 1980s. I wonder if there are any other travel books by Indians in China or Chinese in India (Xuanzang excluded, etc.).

Additional Authors: André Maurois, James E. Irby, Donald A. Yates
My Review: This was the first Borges I have read (thanks to David Foster Wallace for the suggestion). The stories that really stick with me from this collection are "The Library of Babel" and "The Immortals". I'd like to come back around later and read some of the books that these stories were collected from, perhaps after reading some of his inspirations so I can get a better feel for his logic, metaphysics, etc.

Title: Perfectly Reasonable Deviations (from the Beaten Track): The Letters of Richard P. Feynman
Author: Richard P. Feynman
My Review:
In a letter to Koichi Mano, 3 Feb 1966:

It seems that the influence of your teacher has been to give you a false idea of what are the worthwhile problems. The worthwhile problems are the ones you can really solve or help solve, the ones you can really contribute something to. A problem is grand in science if it lies before us unsolved and we see some way for us to make a little headway into it.


In a letter to Mark Minguillon, 23 April 1976:

Don't pay attention to "authorities," think for yourself.

Title: What Do You Care What Other People Think: Further Adventures of a Curious Character
Author: Richard P. Feynman
My Review:
The second half of the book, regarding Feynman's time on the Rogers Commission to determine the cause of the Space Shuttle Challenger wreck, was the most interesting:

Let us make recommendations to ensure that NASA officials deal in a world of reality, understanding technological weaknesses and imperfections well enough to be actively trying to eliminate them. They must live in a world of reality in comparing the coasts and utility of the shuttle to other methods of entering space. And they must be realistic in making contracts and in estimating the costs and difficulties of each project. Only realistic flight schedules should be proposed—schedules that have a reasonable chance of being met. If in this way the government would not support NASA, then so be it. NASA owes it to the citizens from whom it asks support to be frank, honest, and informative, so that these citizens can make the wisest decisions for the use of their limited resources.

For a successful technology, reality must take precedence over public relations, for Nature can not be fooled.

Title: A Supposedly Fun Thing I'll Never Do Again: Essays and Arguments
Author: David Foster Wallace
My Review: Halfway through, I was on the fence about giving this three or four stars. On one hand (the three star hand) I had trouble keeping up with the TV/irony/fiction essay. On the other hand I loved the Illinois State Fair essay because DFW did a hell of a good job deconstructing an event that represents growing up for me. Then I read the David Lynch essay--a director whose movies I have not seen--and the book became a solid four-star book. Then I read the Michael Joyce/tennis essay and decided the book was worth five stars. There was something way beyond tennis in that essay--the composition and focus that separates the very good from the great--that I really enjoyed.

Title: Fear and Loathing: on the Campaign Trail '72
Author: Hunter S. Thompson
My Review:
The whole framework of the presidency is getting out of hand. It's come to the point where you almost can't run unless you can cause people to salivate and whip on each other with big sticks. You almost have to be a rock star to get the kind of fever you need to survive in American politics.

And, as Hunter S. Thompson might have said: Indeed.

There are two themes of the 1972 presidential campaign that Thompson focuses on in FL72: (1) the madness--meaning, the madness of being locked into a campaign and riding all of the highs and lows like a drug addict, a comparison Thompson is eminently qualified to make; and (2) the technical details.

What I discovered from FL72 is that the technical details of how campaigns are run are more interesting than the emotions a campaign evokes. The opening quote here, about voters whipping on each other with sticks, is why I try to stay away from following politics. Just the idea of the frenzies that people will allow themselves to be whipped into gives me a headache, and I'd rather stay away from that crowd--if only to avoid becoming one of them. So, instead of reading about a comparison of ideologies, I enjoyed getting a flavor of what it's like to be in a campaign: the advance men, the field organizers, the perception compared to the reality of candidates' positions.

I found most of the details about how the Democratic National Convention works to be incomprehensible. There is a long piece in the middle of the book, a transcript recorded among Thompson and two of George McGovern's staff on the beach in Miami, that describes roll calls and challenges and delegate maneuvering and other things that I couldn't grasp and don't have the heart to read again. On one hand, it was an awful, boring bit of description; on the other hand, I suppose that that's how the process of selecting a presidential candidate works and that was the point of the oppressive drudgery of that section.

My favorite aspect of FL72 is the angle from which it is written, that is, the complete lack of pretense about his own feelings while covering the campaign. I prefer that Thompson revels in his own bias instead of passing off his writing as, well, fair and balanced.

So much for Objective Journalism. Don't bother to look for it here--not under any byline of mine; or anyone else I can think of. With the possible exception of things like box scores, race results, and stock market tabulations, there is no such thing as Objective Journalism. The phrase itself is a pompous contradiction in terms.

Finally, if you've decided that you want to read some--any--Hunter S. Thompson, don't start with [b:Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas|7745|Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas A Savage Journey to the Heart of the American Dream|Hunter S. Thompson|http://photo.goodreads.com/books/1255576700s/7745.jpg|1309111]. Don't. It will still be there later. Start with this book or [b:The Great Shark Hunt|10878|The Great Shark Hunt Strange Tales from a Strange Time|Hunter S. Thompson|http://photo.goodreads.com/books/1166334568s/10878.jpg|1005676] (which also contains selections from FL72) instead. Either of these will give you an understanding that there is wisdom and keenness mixed in with the madness of Thompson's writing--perhaps even a brilliant mind at work despite, or because of, that madness.

Title: A Short History of Nearly Everything: 2.0
Author: Bill Bryson
My Review:
What I enjoyed in this book had very little to do with the many bits of trivia contained in it, although that was indeed interesting. It was interesting, for example, to consider how improbable it is for fossils to form and how few fossils establish the basis of our knowledge of dinosaurs, humans, etc. This was something I had never considered.

What I really enjoyed in this book were the stories of the people who made -- and stole and obscured and prevented and so on -- the discoveries that our fundamental knowledge of the universe is based on. I had never considered that concepts such as the taxonomy of living things, plate tectonics, the structure of atoms, etc., were defined as much by the politics, caprice, and egotism of people as they were by theories and observations. I thought this was all absolutely established. It is not.

One further thing I liked about the book is that [a:Bill Bryson|7|Bill Bryson|http://photo.goodreads.com/authors/1189096502p2/7.jpg] shows some humility in his discussion of the topics. From the very beginning he says, "I don't know anything." Then he methodically walks through how he learned about the topics, including many names of people and books where the curious can go to learn more. When the topics become murky or controversial, it is easy to tell when he is taking a stand on one side or when he is guessing to synthesize varying viewpoints.

I enjoyed the book. It was a good reminder that understanding "why" is even more important than understanding "what." Now I will try to rearm myself with that same curiosity.

Title: The Snows of Kilimanjaro and Other Stories
Author: Ernest Hemingway
My Review: This is my first time reading any of Ernest Hemingway's works. My favorite stories in The Snows of Kilimanjaro are the final two, "Fifty Grand" and "The Short Happy Life of Francis Macomber." I enjoyed how thoroughly I felt I was transported to the location of both of these stories. As much as I liked his use of dialogue to move the story -- I liked "The Killers" for this very reason -- it was the way Hemingway placed me in the environment with Jack and Francis that I liked the most.
